# Styling Standards & CSS Module Guidelines

**Comprehensive guide for styling decisions, CSS module usage, and design token patterns in the Corso codebase.**

## TL;DR
- **Tailwind-first**: Use Tailwind utilities for 90% of styling needs
- **CSS modules**: Use for complex component-specific styles, animations, or when Tailwind becomes unwieldy
- **Design tokens**: Always use tokens for colors, spacing, typography - never hardcode values
- **Consistency**: Follow existing patterns in hero, market-insights, roi, and chat CSS modules

## ğŸ¯ When to Use CSS Modules vs Tailwind

### âœ… Use Tailwind Utilities (Default Choice)

**Use Tailwind for:**
- Standard layout (flex, grid, positioning)
- Common spacing (padding, margin, gap)
- Typography (font sizes, weights, line heights)
- Colors (using design tokens via Tailwind classes)
- Borders and border radius
- Standard responsive breakpoints
- Hover/focus states
- Most component styling

**Example:**
```tsx
<div className="flex items-center gap-4 px-6 py-4 border border-border bg-surface rounded-lg hover:bg-surface-hover">
  <h2 className="text-2xl font-semibold text-foreground">Title</h2>
</div>
```

### âœ… Use CSS Modules (Specific Cases)

**Use CSS modules when:**
1. **Complex animations** that require keyframes or complex transitions
2. **Component-specific responsive behavior** that's hard to express in Tailwind
3. **Complex selectors** (e.g., `.parent:hover .child`, pseudo-elements)
4. **CSS custom properties** that need to be scoped to a component
5. **Performance-critical styles** that benefit from CSS-in-CSS optimization
6. **Third-party integration** requiring specific CSS patterns

**Example:**
```css
/* components/chat/chat.module.css */
.messagesContainer {
  flex: 1;
  min-height: 0;
  overflow-y: auto;
  background: hsl(var(--background));
  display: flex;
  flex-direction: column;
  justify-content: flex-end;
}

.messagesList {
  max-width: var(--chat-container-max-w-sm);
  padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .messagesList {
    max-width: var(--chat-container-max-w-md);
  }
}
```

## ğŸ“ CSS Module Patterns

### File Naming
- Use `[component-name].module.css` in the same directory as the component
- Example: `components/chat/chat.module.css`

### Class Naming
- Use camelCase for class names: `.chatWindow`, `.messagesContainer`
- Be descriptive: `.composerContainer` not `.container`
- Use component prefix for clarity: `.chat-*`, `.hero-*`, `.roi-*`

### Import Pattern
```tsx
import styles from './chat.module.css';

// Use bracket notation for TypeScript compatibility
<div className={styles['chatWindow']}>
```

### Token Usage in CSS Modules
Always use design tokens via CSS custom properties:
```css
/* âœ… CORRECT: Use tokens */
.messagesContainer {
  background: hsl(var(--background));
  border: 1px solid hsl(var(--border));
  padding: var(--space-md);
  border-radius: var(--radius-lg);
}

/* âŒ INCORRECT: Hardcoded values */
.messagesContainer {
  background: #ffffff;
  border: 1px solid #e5e7eb;
  padding: 16px;
  border-radius: 8px;
}
```

## ğŸ¨ Design Token Usage

### Token Categories

#### Colors
```css
/* Use semantic color tokens */
background: hsl(var(--background));
color: hsl(var(--foreground));
border-color: hsl(var(--border));
```

#### Spacing
```css
/* Use spacing tokens */
padding: var(--space-md);
gap: var(--space-lg);
margin-bottom: var(--space-sm);
```

#### Typography
```css
/* Use typography tokens */
font-size: var(--text-lg);
line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);
```

#### Domain-Specific Tokens
```css
/* Chat tokens */
max-width: var(--chat-container-max-w-sm);
padding: var(--chat-composer-padding-x);

/* Sidebar tokens */
width: var(--sb-width-expanded);
height: var(--sb-item-h);
```

### Token Naming Conventions
- **Global tokens**: `--primary`, `--foreground`, `--space-md`
- **Domain tokens**: `--chat-*`, `--sb-*`, `--hero-*`
- **Component tokens**: `--chat-composer-*`, `--chat-bubble-*`

